# linux_abi/api_scsi.ad
#
# SCSI mid-layer (scsi_mod.ko) gap-closure shims.
#
# scsi_mod.ko is the SCSI mid-layer — Linux's generic framework for
# every SCSI-shaped block device. Loading scsi_mod.ko (Debian 6.1.0-32
# build) under the L-shim unlocks the entire family of stock Linux
# SCSI drivers (sd_mod, sr_mod, st_mod, libata, mpt3sas, megaraid_sas,
# qla2xxx, virtio_scsi, ...). It is THE foundational module for "any
# Linux storage driver" — making it loadable here is the leverage
# point for everything downstream.
#
# Strategic frame: the goal is L-series ABI maximalism. Every UND
# symbol scsi_mod.ko consumes that isn't already covered by L<=68 +
# api_e1000e/ahci/nvme/etc. gets a shim here. The shims approximate
# Linux's contract semantics (return value shape, output-param
# initialisation) tightly enough that scsi_mod.ko's init_module
# completes, the cross-module __ksymtab gets populated, and subsequent
# .ko loads (libata.ko in particular) find scsi_mod's exports via the
# loader's ksymtab fallback path.
#
# scsi_mod.ko's UND surface against the post-L68 + e1000e + ahci +
# nvme shim set:
#
#   * Total UND in scsi_mod.ko       : 261
#   * Already in L<=68 / api_*       : 198
#   * Net new exports this file adds : ~83 (scsi-only) + 13 (shared
#                                       with libata) = 96 declarations
#   * Naming prefix: "_scs_" marks the SCSI gap-closure batch.
#
# Categories (gap analysis):
#
#   * 30 blk_* / blk_mq_* / blk_queue_* — block-layer extensions
#     scsi_mod consumes beyond what the existing api_block.ad +
#     api_nvme.ad set covers. Most are queue-tuning + tag-set ops
#     (max_segments, segment_size, virt_boundary, dma_alignment),
#     queue-quiesce / freeze / unfreeze, the runtime-PM
#     pre/post_runtime_{suspend,resume} variants, and the request-
#     execution wrappers (blk_execute_rq, blk_rq_map_*).
#
#   * 8 sg_*/scsi_* — scatter-gather table helpers + low-level SCSI
#     primitives that operate on struct scsi_sense_hdr (the sense-
#     buffer parser). sg_alloc_table_chained / sg_free_table_chained
#     drive the chained scatterlist used for large transfers;
#     scsi_normalize_sense + scsi_build_sense_buffer construct the
#     standard sense-data format every SCSI device returns.
#
#   * 7 sbitmap_* / ida_* — generic bit-allocator + IDR/IDA helpers
#     scsi_mod uses for tag allocation and per-host ID assignment.
#
#   * 5 transport_* / attribute_container_* — SCSI transport layer
#     plumbing (fibre channel, iSCSI, SAS). scsi_mod links these
#     unconditionally even though only specific transport drivers
#     register containers.
#
#   * 5 trace_* — trace-event sequence-buffer helpers. We don't have
#     trace event support; stubs return no-op success.
#
#   * 16 misc — devm helpers, sysfs helpers, ACPI hooks, kasprintf,
#     kmem_cache_create_usercopy, hex_dump_to_buffer, jiffies/clock_t
#     conversions, simple_strtoull, register_sysctl_table,
#     platform_bus, vscnprintf, etc.
#
# Stub philosophy: scsi_mod's init_module is the init-cold path the
# loader exercises. Most of these shims execute only during
# (a) module init (bus_register, class_register, kmem_cache_create_*)
# or (b) device-probe time (scsi_scan_host -> blk_mq_alloc_tag_set ->
# device_add). For (a) we return 0/success; for (b) we return
# best-effort defaults the caller can survive on init-cold paths.
#
# Compiler-quirk notes (same as api_ahci.ad):
#   * Adder reserves `bytes`, `match`, `case`, `type`, `field`, `file` —
#     renamed where they would collide.
#   * No default-valued params; every arg is passed explicitly.
#   * Ops-vtable DATA buffers are zero-initialised globals.

from linux_abi.exports import _add_export
from kernel.printk.printk import printk0, printk1
from mm.slab import kmalloc, kzalloc, kfree


# =====================================================================
# DATA buffers
# =====================================================================
#
# scsi_mod has a handful of exported global tables. We expose zeroed
# buffers as the symbol addresses.
#
#   scsi_command_size_tbl — uint8[16] giving the byte length of each
#     SCSI CDB opcode group (groups 0..7). Real values matter when a
#     driver calls scsi_command_size(cmd[0]); we populate with the
#     Linux constants (6, 10, 10, 12, 16, 12, 0, 0).
#
#   scsi_device_type — array of const char * names for type codes
#     0..0x1F ("Direct-Access", "Sequential-Access", ...). Used by
#     /proc/scsi/scsi; zero buffer is safe (NULL pointers render as
#     "(null)" through printk).
#
#   platform_bus — struct bus_type definition for the platform bus.
#     Some drivers reference &platform_bus when iterating busses;
#     zeroed buffer is fine for init-cold (no iteration runs).
#
#   system_long_wq — struct workqueue_struct * for the "long" wq.
#     Stub points at a 64-byte buffer; alloc_workqueue+queue_work
#     elsewhere in api_kthread.ad treat any non-NULL wq as live.

scs_scsi_command_size_tbl_buf: Array[16, uint8]
scs_scsi_device_type_buf:      Array[512, uint64]
scs_platform_bus_buf:          Array[512, uint8]
scs_system_long_wq_buf:        Array[64, uint8]
scs_system_long_wq_ptr:        uint64 = 0


def _scs_init_data():
    # Populate scsi_command_size_tbl with the real Linux values.
    # include/scsi/scsi_common.h: COMMAND_SIZE(opcode>>5)
    scs_scsi_command_size_tbl_buf[0] = 6
    scs_scsi_command_size_tbl_buf[1] = 10
    scs_scsi_command_size_tbl_buf[2] = 10
    scs_scsi_command_size_tbl_buf[3] = 12
    scs_scsi_command_size_tbl_buf[4] = 16
    scs_scsi_command_size_tbl_buf[5] = 12
    scs_scsi_command_size_tbl_buf[6] = 0
    scs_scsi_command_size_tbl_buf[7] = 0
    # system_long_wq pointer points at its buffer (dereferences as
    # non-NULL wq).
    scs_system_long_wq_ptr = cast[uint64](&scs_system_long_wq_buf[0])


